Equivalence Partitioning and Boundary Value Analysis

Introduction
Equivalence Partitioning (EP) and Boundary Value Analysis (BVA) are important Black Box Testing techniques used in software testing. These techniques help testers design effective test cases while reducing the total number of test inputs.
Instead of testing every possible value, testers select representative values that provide maximum defect detection with minimum effort.

1. Equivalence Partitioning (EP)
Definition
Equivalence Partitioning is a testing technique where input data is divided into different groups called equivalence classes or partitions. Each group contains values that are expected to behave in the same way.
Instead of testing all values in a group, the tester selects one representative value from each partition.

Concept
Inputs are divided into:
            Valid partitions (acceptable inputs)
            Invalid partitions (unacceptable inputs)
If one value works correctly, it is assumed that all values in that partition will behave similarly.

Example 1 – Age Validation

System accepts age between 18 and 60.

Partitions
Partition Type	             Range
Invalid	                  Less than 18
Valid	                     18 to 60
Invalid              	Greater than 60

Test Cases
Test Value	                 Reason
   15	                 Invalid partition (<18)
   30	                   Valid partition
   65	                Invalid partition (>60)

 Only 3 test cases instead of testing all ages.

Example 2 – Marks Field
Allowed marks: 0–100

Partitions:
Invalid          below 0
Valid            0–100
Invalid        above 100

Test values:
-5
50
120

Advantages of Equivalence Partitioning

Reduces number of test cases.
Saves testing time.
Provides good test coverage.
Easy to design test cases.

Limitations
May miss errors at boundary limits.
Requires proper understanding of input ranges.

2. Boundary Value Analysis (BVA)
Definition
Boundary Value Analysis is a testing technique that focuses on testing values at the edges or boundaries of input ranges because defects are most likely to occur at boundary limits.

Concept
Instead of testing middle values, testers check:
                                  Minimum value
                                  Maximum value
                             Just below minimum
                             Just above minimum
                            Just below maximum
                            Just above maximum

Example 1 – Age Validation

Valid range: 18–60

Boundary               Test Values
Test Value	           Description
   17	                Below minimum
   18              	Minimum boundary
   19	                Above minimum
   59	               Below maximum
   60	              Maximum boundary
   61	               Above maximum

These values help detect edge-condition defects.

Advantages of Boundary Value Analysis
Detects edge-related defects.
Highly effective technique.
Improves test accuracy.

Limitations

Works mainly for range-based inputs.
Cannot identify all logical errors.

                     Difference Between EP and BVA
Equivalence Partitioning	                     Boundary Value Analysis
Divides inputs into groups	                  Focuses on boundary limits
Tests representative values                    	Tests edge values
Reduces test cases	                           Finds boundary defects
General input testing	                          Edge condition testing

Combined Use of EP & BVA
In real testing, both techniques are used together:
EP   reduces number of test cases.
BVA  ensures boundary conditions are tested.

This combination provides maximum coverage with minimum effort.

Equivalence Partitioning and Boundary Value Analysis are efficient test design techniques that help testers create optimized test cases. 
EP ensures coverage of input groups, while BVA verifies system behavior at critical boundary values. 
Together, they improve software quality and reduce testing time.
